      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates <2% change in all three QoIs between the production mesh and a uniformly refined mesh at 1.5× element density.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was performed on the non-cannulated screw geometry. The production mesh (≈420 000 elements, hex-dominant) exhibited less than 1.4% variation in stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement relative to the fine mesh. Richardson extrapolation GCI values were below 2% throughout."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals below 1×10⁻⁶ for all load steps; energy balance error below 0.1%.",
      "rationale": "Static implicit analyses converged to force residual norms below 1×10⁻⁷ at every load increment. Energy balance was monitored throughout; maximum imbalance was 0.04%. No spurious hourglassing or element distortion warnings were generated. Gradation 2 achieved against Gradation 1 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of model setup by a second analyst; checklist-based QA review completed before each simulation run.",
      "rationale": "A formal peer-review checklist was completed by a second FDA analyst before submission of each simulation batch. Boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, and load application were independently verified. No use errors were identified during review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum linear-elastic model with bilinear kinematic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V; frictional contact at screw-rod interface; model physics justified by published material characterization data.",
      "rationale": "The model employs continuum mechanics with bilinear isotropic hardening calibrated to Ti-6Al-4V tensile coupon data from the same material lot. Frictional contact (μ=0.2) at the screw-rod interface is consistent with published tribological data for titanium alloy interfaces. Geometric nonlinearity is activated to capture large-displacement effects at 40 mm crosshead travel. Model form is appropriate for the QoIs and COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometry measured from the same production lot as test specimens; dimensional uncertainty quantified by CMM measurements on five screws.",
      "rationale": "Young's modulus, yield strength, and ultimate tensile strength were measured from three tensile coupons machined from the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock as the test constructs. Screw geometry was digitised via CMM on five randomly selected screws; nominal CAD dimensions were updated to reflect measured mean values. Input uncertainty propagated via ±2σ sensitivity runs; QoI sensitivity to input variation is below 3%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs tested; specimens traceable to production lot; inter-laboratory reproducibility confirmed.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled and tested across two independent laboratories. All specimens were drawn from the same production lot and are traceable via lot number. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for stiffness was 4.2%, confirming reproducibility. Sample size satisfies the Gradation 3 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios; at minimum two load levels or two fixation configurations tested.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration at a single crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min). While the protocol is standardised, only one test condition was evaluated, precluding assessment of rate or configuration sensitivity. Achieved level is Gradation 2 against the Gradation 3 requirement; this is a known gap accepted by the credibility assessment team given the regulatory context of the submission."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions and material properties demonstrably equivalent to test setup; discrepancies quantified and within measurement uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "FEA boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry as measured by the testing laboratory. Applied displacement and constraint locations were confirmed against laboratory photographs and fixture drawings. Material property equivalency was established by matching tensile coupon data to the model input deck. All discrepancies between nominal and measured values were below 1.5% and within combined measurement uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs; percentage difference between FEA prediction and experimental mean < 10% for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "For all three QoIs, the validation metric E/uval (ratio of model-experiment difference to combined validation uncertainty) was below 1.96 (stiffness: 1.12, yield force: 1.44, force at 40 mm: 0.97). Percentage differences between FEA ensemble mean and experimental mean were 4.1%, 7.8%, and 3.5% respectively, all within the 10% acceptance bound. Both acceptance criteria satisfied at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in the FDA guidance for pedicle screw submission under ASTM F1717. Each QoI maps directly to a clinically relevant failure mode: stiffness to load-sharing with bone, yield force to permanent deformation risk, and force at 40 mm to catastrophic fracture risk. QoI relevance is fully established."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario geometry, loading, and boundary conditions are representative of the COU; any extrapolation is bounded and justified.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the exact non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry, UHMWPE test block material, and ASTM F1717 loading configuration that constitute the COU. No extrapolation in geometry or loading regime is required. The FEA model is applied within its validated domain. Validation activity relevance to the COU is fully established at Gradation 3."
    }
